column168: NOTE: cost of damaged cargo is estimated - awaiting final figure on claim form  Car cut in front of driver.  Driver braked quickly and hard.  Straps over the pallet of adhesives did not tear but it weakend the cardboard allowing the strap to sink down some allowing containers to slide out or the strap and shrink wrap.  10 containers opened upon impact with the ground spilling part of the 5 gallons of adhesive that they held.    Bergen County Police responded and a local hazmat crew.  They spread stay dry and shoveled the stay dry and the spilled adhesive into large containers.    The spill was contained on the macadam in lanes 2 and 3 of a 4 lane highway. The highway never completely shut down and there was no soil contamination.

column168: Continental Airlines customer offered checked luggage for TSA screening for travel SEA/IAH/PTY.  TSA Screening machine discovered battery in customer luggage. The TSA screening agent pulled the battery out of the bag and set it on the metal table the battery in a manner to cause positive & negative contacts to touch metal screening table.  The battery started sparking, smoking and pulsing.  Local fire department responded and mitigated threat,  It was later discovered that TA agent placed the metal terminals on the metal screening table.  This created a connection between the positive and negative conductors, which caused the battery to spark, smoke, pulse and expand.  The battery was removed from the metal screening table.

column168: A BNSF yard switch crew reported a product slosh release from the top of GATX 49581 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) during normal rail movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and a nearby BNSF response contractor was called to eliminate the leak source and remediate spillage on the tank shell. The responders removed intact seal WIC 368556 on the valve housing cover to inspect the valves. All valves were found closed with their closure plugs secure. The manway cover's intact seal WIC 368555 was removed to inspect the manway gasket. The manway securement bolts were found less than tool tight and the manway gasket was found out of position; both attributing to and preventing a good seal. The responders cleaned and correctly repositioned the manway gasket; and properly tool tightened all six manway securement bolts by 2000 hrs. CDT, 8/4/09. New seals numbered SRS 000363 and 000367 were affixed onto the valve housing cover and the manway respectively. The spillage on the top and side shell of GATX 49581 was neutralized with an application of a magnesium oxide solution by 2110 hrs. CDT, 8/04/09. No ground impact from the spillage was evident. No further product release was reported from subsequent rail movements.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A van trailer was about to be moved from the in transit storage yard to the intended waste disposal facility.  The driver noticed material dripping from the trailer onto the ground.  An emergency response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A drum was found to be leaking and contaminated the pallets adjoining it.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container and the trailer was taken to the intended waste disposal facility where it was unloaded and cleaned with a cleaning compound.  The material which had leaked onto the ground was removed and placed into a salvage box and also taken to the waste disposal facility.  Investigation showed that the drum had been punctured by a nail protruding from a pallet.
column169: The origin location was notified of the incident and reviewed proper loading procedures with all applicable employees.  Pallets are to be double checked for protuding objects such as nails and not to be used if in poor condition.

column168: This drum was loaded onto another carriers truck on 08/10/09 and delivered to our warehouse on 08/13/09.  On 08/18/09 it was loaded onto our truck and departed our Bartow, FL terminal.  The driver parked in a parking lot in Lake Wales, FL while he ate his lunch.  Before beginning the drive again, the driver inspected the truck and found material dripping from the back door of the trailer.  The driver created a dike with absorbent material to prevent the leaking material from spreading further and then called our emergency number.  Emergency Response teams were dispatched from our terminal and a private contractor was also dispatched.      The drum had developed internal pressure that resulted in a 3" crack near the top of the body of the drum, releasing the material onto the floor of the trailer.  Most material was contained within the trailer, however, approximately 5 gallons were released to the asphalt parking lot.    The leaking drum was overpacked.  All absorbent material was collected and the affected area was treated with lime to neutralize the acid.  This was also collected and all cleanup material was placed into a drum for disposal at a licensed disposal facility.  The truck returned to our terminal and was off-loaded.  The floor of the truck was then decontaminated.
column169: Better training is required for generators of hazardous wastes, particularly when different materials are combined to form solutions of more than one hazardous material.  Better research is needed to find compatible packaging for solutions of more than one hazardous material when they are mixed together.

column168: After cargo acceptance and during the screening process it was determined that there were chemicals in the package tendered. An MSDS was requested from the freight forwarder. The MSDS that was supplied by the forwarder was ambiguous with respect to transportation restrictions and since the flash point stated was 93 degrees F. we requested a more definitive MSDS. The same exact MSDS was supplied by the forwarder, with one change, that being; the words(IATA: Not Regulated) had been added to the MSDS. At that time we querried the manufacturer who pointed us to their website, assuring us that the web site had the most up-to-date MSDS' for their products. We checked said web site and discovered that there was indeed no verbage to the effect (IATA: Not Regulated) on their MSDS. At this point we suspected that the MSDS had been altered to facilitate transport and notified the 24 office of the FAA. The FAA representative then investigated and directed us to file this report.
column169: Better training for the freight forwarders.

column168: When unloading freight from a trailer material handler struck two boxes that were staged on the pallet that he was unloading with the blades of his forklift. As a result two cans that were inside the boxes were slightly punctured contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged cans and boxes.

When moving freight on dock it was discovered that one of the jerricans that was staged on pallet was leaking from top. Further investigation discovered that there was a small hole on top of the jerrican. There was some other freight that was staged on top of the pallet of jerricans and it is our opinion that either the top freight was too heavy or there was something protruding from this shipment that caused this puncture which led to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged jerrican.

When unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a loose drum lying on its side from not being properly secured while in transit. Further investigation revealed that the drum had a very small pinhole in it as a result that contributed to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent and damaged drum was repaired with drum repair putty and placed into a recovery container.

The origin terminal, although right in action, was not effective enough to protect freight from damage. It seems as though, the drum had was allowed to move just enough to break pallet. Once the pallet broke, the rope was not strong enough to hole the drum in place.the amount released was only 5 OZ. the cap came open during transit after drum had fallen over, not much leaked out but it is understandable this could have been present for most of the trip.Once the spill was found, container was placed upward to contain spill.
column169: if a single drum is being shipped, this drum should not be placed onto a palet, but onto the floor of the trailer with cardboard underneath, the drum should be securely tied to wall of the trailer with no slack given, you should place Hazmat at the rear of the trailer if possible for easy access.

column168: This railcar was observed leaking during switching operations.  The railcar was isolated.  Upon closer inspection, the product was coming from under cover over valves. Shipper seal # 005142 was removed for inspection. Upon inspection the liquid  valve was found to be leaking. Valve was closed, however the plug was only finger tight. Plug was made tool tight and the leak stopped. Cover closed and CN seal # CNDG 000115 was put in place. Car was then re-inspected and no other leaks found. Car released for transportation.

column168: A shipment of hazardous material was at the ten day storage facility and being moved to a staging area for sampling prior to acceptance at the intended waste disposal facility. A response crew was notified and donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and contained the spill with absorbent pads. The drum and pads were overpacked into a suitable salvage drum and, after sampling, was accepted and disposed of at the intended waste disposal facility.

column168: IBC was being loaded onto a delivery unit with a forklift at which time the bottom valve became disconnected and shot across the floor of the dock.  The contents of the IBC immediately began to empty out inside the trailer until the IBC was empty.  An emergency response company was immediately contacted for clean up of material and remediation of the area.    Further inspection of the valve area by the clean up company showed that the bottom gravity flow valve was held in place by a plastic retaining ring and two small bolts to crimp it closed around the valve.  The plastic retaining ring had broken/seperated at the bolt area thus releasing the valve from the body of the IBC.    Due to the amount of liquid spilled and clean up, removal of material, and disposal the packaging specification were not able to be obtained.

column62: Missing Component or Device; Valve Open
column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Safety Inspector reported observing UTLX 61459 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car) in the railyard with commodity on the top and also the side shell of this tank car. A detailed inspection revealed that the protective housing cover was not secured (neither pinned nor sealed) and both closure plugs for the liquid and air/vapor line valves were not applied, thus the possible leak source. A BNSF contract responder was called to decontaminate UTLX 61459 and secure the liquid and vapor valves. The responder reported that both valves (liquid and vapor) were in the closed position but evidence of liquids by-passing the closed liquid valve and product vapor by-passing the closed vapor valve were present. Both valves and closure plugs were cleaned. Teflon tape and Gasoila thread sealant were applied to the threaded portion of the closure plugs. The plugs were applied in their respective orifices and tool tightened. Afterwards, no further product detection was observed and the protective housing cover was secured and sealed with seal numbered 00031682. The spillage on the tank shell of UTLX 61459 that didn't evaporate was wiped.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Around 7:50 AM an employee was loading the daily deliveries on to a trailer.  The loading process is done from the dock via Forklift.  While the employee was entering a trailer to load an IBC that contained Sulfuric Acid  the material suddenly shifted causing the IBC to flip on it’s side.  When the IBC landed on the dock the impact caused the top cap to blow off from the IBC causing material to spill out.  Approximately 50 gallons was released onto and below the dock area.  The other employees donned on their PPE while the forklift operator was able to lift the tote high enough to stop the flow of the acid.  Quickly the operator also donned on his PPE. To prevent injury and splashing the IBC was covered with a plastic sheet while the IBC was rested to it’s upright position.  The spilled material was quickly dike off and neutralized with a large amount of Soda Ash.   After the acid was able to be neutralized with the soda ash, it was swept up and placed in the proper containers and then staged in the satellite accumulation area. The affected area was then washed down.  The water that was used to wash down the area was vacuumed and pumped into the neutralization pit.  The rest of the material contained in the IBC will be transferred to another IBC before it is sent back to the Odessa branch to be tested in order to see if the material can be topped off and to be resold.  The IBC, (serial #OD11892) that was involved in the spill will also be sent back to Odessa to be inspected and retested to insure that the IBC is safe for reuse.
column169: THIS INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTALBE IF THE EMPLOYEE WOULD HAVE SLOWED DOWN AND TAKEN MORE CAREFUL TIME TO LOAD THE IBC ONTO THE TRAILER.  EMPLOYEE FORKLIFT TRAINING WAS CHECKED FOR CURRENCY WHICH IT WAS UP TO DATE.  THE EMPLOYEE AGREED THAT IT WAS A PREVENTABLE INCIDENT.  TRAINING WAS ALSO TAKEN AGAIN TO REMIND THE EMPLOYEE THE SAFEST OPERATONAL PROCESSES IN OPERATION OF A FORKLIFT AND LOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: On 08/08/2009 at 01:05 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Montgomery yard discovered GATX90430, a residue tank car of Dimethylamine, Anhydrous leaking from the secondary securement plug on the liquid line valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Taminco Methylamines, LLC and the consignee, VLS Recovery Services, LL, were notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2009080800105). SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found that the secondary securement plug on the liquid line valve was less tool tight. SWS personnel tightened the secondary securement plug and the leak stopped.  The car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NARRI: 5(1+5+0) X (2+0) = 60  Cause Code: 120
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shippers location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor's in transit storage area for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantties of material for continued transportation.  During the course of this layover, an inspection of the load identified that 2 of the containers ruputered due to an over pressuization condition that we believe to have been cause by a chemical reaction and an increae in ambient temperature.  Once identified, an emergecny reposnse team was assembled and the the shippin gpapers were reviewed.  Following all health and safety protocols, the identify of the containers in question were found and a plan was developed to enter the trailer, remove all unaffected containers and intiate the clean-up.  Please note all material released remained within the trailer.  Once the containers were identified, a suitable absorbent was used to collect all freee liquids and this was containerized along with the damaged containers for disposal at a licensed waste management facility.  In addition, all of the drums that contained the same waste stream were segregated and the closures were removed to releive any pressure that was potneitally building in the remaining drums.  It was decided to accept these containers at the Clean Harbor's hazardous waste treatement facility adjacent to the in transit facility rather than ship them for continued transportation.  All mateiral was treated and disposed of safely.  The final step was to decontaminate the interior of the trailer.  all supplies used to decontaminate the trailer were containerized and disposed of at an appropriate waste management facility.
column169: At the time the containers were accepted for transportation, no evidence of pressurization was observed nor was any adverse observations identified when the containers were consolidated for continuing transportation.  What is believed to have happened was that one consitiuient of the waste stream (sodium bicarbonate) reacted with a water component in the waste stream and released carbon disoxide as the ambient temperature began to rise.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper of this waste stream has put into place a new process by which they will pretreat the waste to consume all of the sodium bicarbonate beofre the offer for transportation.  Each shipment will be accompanied by a signed certification that the material has been treated and that the sodium bicarbonate is no longer an active component of the waste stream.

column168: This railcar was observed leaking during switching operations.  The railcar was isolated.  Upon closer inspection, the manway bolts were found to be loose.  The manway gasket was inspected and found to be worn.  The manway gasket was replaced, the manway bolts were tightened and the leak was secured.  No injuries.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver stopped at Clean Harbor's 10-day intransit storage location for the purpose of comsolidating less than truck load quantities of material onto a second vehicle for continued transportation.  At the conclusion of the laoding operation, the load was inspected and it was discovered that the fork-lift used to transfer the materials punctured the container allowing a small amount of material to escape onto the side of the container and the floor of the van trailer.  A response team was assembled and the crew, after donning the appropriate protective equipment, entered the trailer and proceeded to place the damaged container into a suitable salvage container.  The material that was released was absorbed using a suitable absorbant material which was then placed in the salvage drum.  The container was secured and was released for continued transportation to the waste management facility where the shipment was recieved for procesing.   PLease note that the incident was reported to the State of Illinois (report IEMA # H20090913) as required by our permit to transport hazardous waste.

column169: SHIPPERS MUST BE AWARE OF HOW MUCH WEIGHT THEY SHIP PER PALLET. PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL .WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: On 08/17/09 at 12:55 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Osborn rail yard in Louisville, KY discovered GATX 32435, a loaded tank car of Hot Ammonium Nitrate liquid, leaking from the bottom of the car at various locations. A CSXT emergency response contractor, Pettit Environmental, was contacted to contain and clean the product spilled from the bottom of the rail car. column168: On August 20, 2009 at 16:11 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Curtis Bay yard discovered GATX32752, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Dover Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report# 2009082000173). Local and state agencies were also notified. React, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the 4-bolt blind flange on the liquid eduction line was missing 3 of 4 securement nuts. React representatives applied 4 new securement nuts and the leak stopped.  React personnel decontaminated the car and cleaned up the spilled material. The car was released for transport.     An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code: 243  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column168: On 08/27/2009 at 11:00 hrs., Hazardous Materials Manager, Chris Machenberg, in the CSXT Mobile Terminal, discovered GATX45009, a loaded tank car of sodium aluminate solution, had a burst rupture disk in the safety vent housing assembly. column168: On morning of 8/30/09 tank car UTLX 641225 was reported leaking by CNIC tower employee while KCS train M-SHCX-29 was moving through CNIC Mayes Yard New Orleans,  The car was immediately stop and KCS mobilized safety qualified emergency responder.  Investigation found approximately   gallon of lading released from a defective vacuum relief valve which was missing the o-ring seal.  The shipper called out Union Tank mobile repair and a new vacuum relief valve was installed. A FRA movement approval was requested on the behalf of the shipper to allow the shipper (Huntsman) to proceed UTLX 641225 to final destination (Charlestown, IN) for unloading and then further movement tank car to home shop for required pressure test.  The emergency responder also reported that the manway was found with 4 of 8 manway bolts hand tight and the liquid and vapor valve secondary plugs were hand tight. For this report, becasue information was not available, quantity gallons was estimated.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: The rear pressure relief valve on a MC-331 cargo tank started venting propane vapors to the atmosphere.  The cargo tank was not being transported at the time of the release but was sitting still, parked at our terminal.  The pressure relief valve date of manufacture is March 2008 and was installed on our cargo tank on December 11, 2008.  The pressure on the cargo tank had 100 psi when we first looked at it after it started venting, 75 degrees.      The event started at 10:45AM and stopped at 16:50HRS.  Fire department used water spray on the vapors, the two lane road was closed to traffic, the railroad was told not to come into the area until an all clear was issued, and members of the Baytown Fire department used monitors in the surrounding area to make sure the vapors were dissipating before reaching any populated areas.
column169: We will be going back to the manufacturer of this pressure relief valve to see if we can identify why their valve failed.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading at customer warehouse, a leak was discovered from one (1) tote inside the trailer.  Tote was secured, and approximately one (1) pint of free product was detected on the trailer floor.  Southern Waste Services of Birmingham, Alabama was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, the tote had been removed from the trailer, accepted by the consignee, and a small area of residual product was detected on the trailer floor.  Southern Waste Services applied soda ash to the affected area, and swept up the spent material, which was containerized into one (1) 5-gallon recovery drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a loose closure on the tote, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and safety to all personnel.

column168: On August 18, 2009 at 00:10 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered ACFX73725, a loaded tank car of Corrosive Liquid, Basic, Inorganic, N.O.S. leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2009-08-18-00036). Summit Contracting, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line plug was less than tool tight. Summit personnel secured the plug with Teflon and tightened the plug and the leak stopped.  Summit representatives decontaminated the car and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 115  NARRI: 5(5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

column168: Undeclared motorcycle found in package. Fuel ( gasoline) was in gas tank. The battery was dry but a package of battery fluid/acid UN2796 with 0.69L was found with the motorcycle. ( package marked and labelled UN2796 battery fluid/acid )   A plastic cord was placed in the fuel tank, the cord was able to be easily ignited, the fire did not go past the section of the coard that was whetted with fuel from the gas tank.   Local FAA advised and they  inspected shipment ( agent Orde Duplessis )  .   Shipment was picked up by the freight forwarder ( Panalpina )with U.S.Customs giving instruction to not sent the shipment.   Shipper insisted motorcycle was non restricted.   When Panalpina told shipper the motorcylce was a HAZMAT / DGR shipper continued to insist that the liquid in the tank was not hazardous.   Corrective action from Freight Forwarder Panalpina/Chicago was to not take take future shipments from this shipper. Also Panalpina stated they will send future shipments of vehicles to a HAZMAT/DGR company to inspect and prepare for air transport.   The shipper was contacted several times by the freighter forwarder Panalpina but the shipper would not admit error at first, then the shipper sent a letter stating " incident...was an isolated incident and unfortunate occurence where hazardous materials were found within the cargo I was involved in shipping "  any further questions to go to his attorney   signed PAVEL PECHERSKIY             ( shipper )   questions to Law Office Yulia Kislyuk 570 Lake Cook Road, Suite 126 , Deerfield IL 60015  847-204-8499 (PHONE )    847-444-1478 ( FAX)

August 19, 2009; 01:50AM: During classification (electronic) operation at Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ, Hump Tower Retarder Operator noted a puff of "smoke" from the top of tank car GATX 61224, load, Hydrocholoric Acid (Class 8, UN1789, PGII, RQ) after it coupled into another car on track #19 Class.    Further investigation by R. Gould, REACT Environmental Services (called out to respond by Conrail) and Conrail's A. Richter, noted the 165# Oseco-style rupture disc had burst as designed.  During inspection, also noted the safety vent frangible disc inspection plug retainer ring (identified as the Rupture Disc Securement Cap for this style valve, SALCO) was broken at about a 1" section.  The retainer ring was removed, along with the ruptured disc.  Viewing inside, there was no evidence of baffle/surge protection.  Car built date noted as "7/93".  Notwithstanding AAR Manual of Standards and Recommended Practices, Section C-III, Specification for Tank Cars, Appendix A4.7.4. (requiring surge pressure reduction devices on new order, converted or rebuilt tank cars effective May 1, 1994), the drawings/installation instructions (supplied by the shipper, PVS Technologies) for the style of SALCO Quick Inspect Safety Vents notes a surge protection device applied.      The ruptured 165# OSECO disc was replaced in kind, the broken threaded retaining ring/securement cap was reapplied at time of inspection.  Car was wiped down of any remaining residue of product that remained (a strong rain storm had passed through the area between the time of reporting of this incident, and the inspection).  Car was moved to the Car Shop area.  Further conversations with actual loader of car, Solvay Solexis, Thorofare, NJ; the waybill shipper/consignee, PVS Technologies, Detroit, MI; and, the product owner, Reagent Chemicals; whereby Reagent arranged for their personnel to respond to the Pavonia Yard Car Shop, replace the broken threaded retaining ring and inspect for a baffled surge protection device.  Later advised via email by car builder, GATC, that this car was supposed to be equipped with a surge protection device.  During observation from the top of the safety vent with the inspection plug, threaded retaining ring and burst disc removed, both REACT and Conrail did not observe another fitting/device between the top of the safety vent assembly and the top of the liquid level inside the car.      Car okayed after final repairs and inspection by Reagent Chemical team, for movement to original destination, PVS Technologies, Detroit, MI, for unloading and further inspection of the safety vent assembly to ascertain the presence or not of the surge protection device.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING FOUR PALLETS THAT HAD BEEN LOADED BEHIND A SKID CONTAINING THREE CYLINDERS OF 2.2 GAS.  THE SKID WITH THE 2.2 GAS WAS NOT BLOCKED IN OR BRACED AND THE CYLINDERS WERE ATTACHED TO THE PALLET USING PLASTIC STRAPPING.  THE SKID SHIFTED FROM WHERE IT HAD BEEN STACKED AND ALL THREE CYLINDERS BROKE OFF THE PALLET.  ONE OF THE THREE CYLINDERS HAD PART OF THE RELEASE VALVE BREAK OFF CAUSING THE 2.2 GAS TO ESCAPE.  THE TRAILER WAS PULLED TO THE YARD TO ALLOW THE PRESSURIZED MATERIAL TO ESCAPE.  THE YRC CHEMICAL HELPLINE WAS CONTACTED VIA HAZMAT ONE AND IT WAS AGREED TO ALLOW NRC ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND TO ASSIT WITH THE PROPER CONTAINMENT OF THE CYLINDER.  THE CYLINDER HAS BEEN PLACED UPRIGHT IN A TRAILER IN OUR YARD WITH THE DOOR OPEN ALLOWING FOR PROPER VENTILLATION OF THE PRODUCT LEAKING OUT.  ONCE ALL PRODUCT HAS OFF GASSED WE WILL CONTACT THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION OF THE DAMAGED CYLINDER.  THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: WHEN THE LOAD PULLED INTO THE STLS FUELLINE IT WAS NOTICED THAT LIQUID WAS RUNNING OUT FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A TOTE OF CVM LIQUID WAS DAMAGED IN TRANSIT. LINED SALVAGE DRUMS, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, WERE USED FOR THE CLEAN-UP AND AFFECTED MATERIALS.  THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: BETTER WAY OF BLOCKING SHOULD HAVE BEEN USED.  THE NOSE SHOULD HAVE BEEN LOADED WITH LIGHT FREIGHT AND THEN COME           BEHIND WITH THE TOTES.  TOTES AND OTHER VARIOUS KINDS OF PACKAGINGS, CONTAINING CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE THEY LEAVE THE ORIGIN.  ALL DRUMS MUST BE BLOCKED AND BRACED TO PREVENT MOVEMENT AND FALLING OVER WHILE THE UNIT IS MOVING.  USE LOAD LOCK BARS, STRAPS AND MTY PALLETS TO ENSURE LOAD IS SAFE AND SECURE BEFORE MOVING.  PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND/OR DUNNAGE.  USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY  SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGE STATING, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM; LIGHT    FREIGHT ON TOP.  USE PLENTLY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER TO MAKE SURE LIDS ON DRUMS ARE SECURED.

column168: Upon arrival of the truck at the pick-up location, 1354 County Road 246, Rifle, CO, it was noticed that there was liquid leaking from the front of the trailer. Spill containment procedures were performed including putting an open empty drum under the leak to collect leaking material. Spill clean-up was performed by North Wind, Inc., Idaho Falls, ID. The trailer was off loaded to get to the leaking drum that was in the nose of the trailer. Once identified the remaining contents of the leaking drum containing 6 inches of liquid and 8 inches of sludge was transferred to a another 55 gallon drum. The trailer floor was cleaned with absorbent pads and the soil under the trailer where the liquid had leaked was removed and placed into a 55 gallon drum. The drum leaked from 2 pinholes in the side of the drum at the first ring from the bottom.
column169: Additional quality assurance and quality control of packaged materials. After the incident the drum that leaked was observed to be in good condition except for the 2 pin holes. The material within the drum was not corrosive and was compatabile with the packaging materials.

column168: A rolloff truck was delivering a loaded box to the ten day temporary storage facility located at the intended waste disposal facility.  While the box was being unloaded, the ram cylinder on the truck stuck while the truck bed was in the raised position.  While the driver was attempting to free the ram cylinder, it suddenly gave loose and the box shifted quickly down the truck bed rails, causing approximately 5 gallons of material to spill onto the ground.  The facility spill response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the material with a suitable absorbent material and loaded it back into the container.  The box was then processed without further incident at the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The truck was taken out of service and driven to the truck maintenance facility for cylinder replacement.  The driver had performed all necessary pre trip vehicle inspections and the truck had performed with no adverse incidents up until this occurrence.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported TILX 192590 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with a product release at its manway closure during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and TILX 192590 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting inspection. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected TILX 192590 during daylight hours and reported all manway securement bolts were tool tight. The intact manway seal was removed and the manway gasket was inspected. The manway gasket was properly positioned, but appeared slightly worn and compressed. It was assumed that this gasket was not sealing properly and a new compatible manway gasket was installed. Afterwards, the manway closure was properly resecured. Response was concluded by 1030 hrs. PDT, 8/30/09. The spillage on the side shell evaporated and no ground impact was evident. No further reports of a product release at the manway closure were reported from TILX 192590 during subsequent movements in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A vapor leak was identified during the loading operation on-site prior to transportation in commerce.  The top manway dome lid, which is not utilized to load the material, was the leak point.  An obstruction was discovered between the dome lid and manway preventing a proper seal of the dome lid gasket.  After the leak was discovered, the loading operation was stopped to eliminate the leak.  The obstruction was extracted and the dome lid was resealed.  An estimated 28 pounds of material leaked into the air.

Driver was transferring 3993 gallons of product from the cargo tank to a 6000 gallon storage tank that had 1280 gallons in it to start.  The storage tank only had a digital readout (no sight glass).  The plant operator who was monitoring the meter walked away briefly.  The overflow alarm sounded but by time the driver could close the valves, 40 gallons had overflowed the tank.  The digital readout was showing 5800 after the overflow.  The spill went into a containment area and the customer cleaned it up.
column169: A plant supervisor will follow-up.  He thinks there may be some issues with calibration and mechanical equipment on their end.

column168: Driver failed to realize that he had two bill of ladings for the product in his cargo tank that was to be split between two different storage tanks at the consignee. He thought he had only 650 gallons in the cargo tank. He didn't see the other BOL for the other 650 gallons.  The storage tank that he was delivering to was 1000 gallons with 100 gallons already in it.  He calculated that it would have plenty of room for the 650 gallons.  He thought the level of the tank would go to 750, the trailer would be empty and the unload would be complete.  By time he realized that the level on the tank was going past the 750 mark and the hose hadn't jumped yet (from being empty), the storage tank overflowed.  driver later realized he had another BOL and actually had 1300 gallons in the cargo tank to start.  The spill went into a containment area around the tank and we hired an emergency response vendor to pump it out.
column169: The driver failed to follow proper procedure.  His work assignment said that he had 1300 gallons but he thought that was an error and never called in to question it.  He has since received remedial training.

column168: On 8-12-09 @ approximatley 5:00 pm MDT. A driver for Univar USA was returning to the branch located at 650 w 800  s  Salt lake City, UT. 84104 when a drum of Hazardous waste fell over inside of the trailer spilling approximatley 3  gals of waste product onto the Univar parking lot. Spill was immediatley cleaned up and properly stored for disposal to a TSDF facility. The container was a open head steel drum which leaked around the top. The lid stayed intact as well as the lock ring.
column169: Univar policy is that no liquid waste is to be picked up for transport with open head drums of any type. Met with drivers and restated Univar policy concerning waste pick ups and proper containers.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper's location to the intended waste management faiclity.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor's in transit storage facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of non bulk packages onto an alternate vehicle for continued transprotation.  During the transfer process, a small amount of liquid escaped from the closure device used to secure the container.  Facility personnel immediately over packaged the container into a suitable salvage drum along with all material used to absorb the released mateials and clean the exterior surface of the original container.  Once secured, the container was loaded for continued transportation to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the containers were accepted for transportation, no visible evidence of leaking while loading or offloading at the Reidsville Facility was observed. It is believed the gasket must have deteriorated and possible drum grabber torque causing the leakage. The plant personnel continues to take steps to assure container integrity and condition while offloading.

column25: Koch Nitrogen International by Martin Gas Terminal
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported GATX 201248 (DOT 112J340W tank car) standing on an adjacent track in the railyard emanating a product odor. This switch crew immediately vacated the area and this area around GATX 201248 was cordoned off. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 201248 and other rail cars adjacent to GATX 201248 and found no odor source or securement deficiencies. Afterwards, BNSF contract responders with air monitoring equipment also inspected GATX 201248 finding its 280.5 psi pressure relief device (PRD) as the source point of the product vapor/odor. Further inspection of the PRD revealed that the seat and stem O-rings had the appearance of a 'compression set' failure, i.e., O-ring flattening at the seal mating/contact surface. The PRD O-rings were replaced in kind by 0805 hrs. CDT, 8/08/09. After the PRD was secured, no further product odor/vapor was detectable by the responder's monitoring equipment. Response was concluded by 0845 hrs. CDT, 8/08/09.  Two BNSF crew members whom initially reported the product odor were treated at a local hospital for inhalation exposure and released.  The side specification stencil on GATX 201248 indicted that the PRD was tested (qualified) in the year 2004 and next due in 2009.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported a product odor emanating from SHPX 221943 (DOT 112J340W tank car) during normal switching operations in the railyard. SHPX 221943 was cordoned off and isolated in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected SHPX 221943. The seal on the protective housing cover was intact and the responder reported hearing a product vapor hiss as the valve's protective housing cover was opened for valve securement inspection. The vapor valve was found to be the source of the vapor hiss. The responder turned this valve's wheel handle approximately 1/4 turn to reseat the valves closure, stopping the vapor release. The closure plug on this valve was tight. No liquid product release was evident. The protective housing cover was closed and pinned, but not resealed, as a suitable replacement seal was not available. Securement was completed at 1215 hrs. CDT, 8/18/09.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column162: SR MGR INDUSTRIAL SAFETY AND ENV
column168: 55-GALLON DRUM WAS SITTING ON A PALLET THAT HAD A SMALL SCREW ON IT.  THE SCREW PUNCHED A SMALL HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: PROPER UNLOADING AND LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN MOVING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  PLACE CUSHIONING BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO BE EASILY DAMAGED.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP.  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column17: ARROW AIR INC DBA ARROW CARGO
column168: Transport Express (US DOT # 508696) was in process of delivering shipment to Arrow Cargo facility for DominoAmjet Inc..  During the process of off-loading truck a strong odor/vapor was noticed; a call was made to Airport Public Safety. The public Safety Officer evaluated the situation and, after thirty minutes, requested the employees to evacuate the building.  The St. Clair Emergency Services Association responded and opened a majority of the boxes containing the MEK.  Their technicians located three boxes that, when opened, had readings at or above 160 ppm VOC.  These three boxes were put into an overpack drum for proper disposal.  The remaining items were returned to the trucker for return to the shipper, as Arrow Cargo had not officially accepted the shipment.

column168: File 25807 - On August 6, 2009, a Quality Carriers tractor-tanker was involved in an incident that involved the release of a UN1993 TOLAD 3030 Additive product.  Approximately 30 gallons of product were released from the dome lid of the tanker.  The local fire deparments and police originally responded, as well as the shipper's response team.  React Environmental was then dispatched to the scene to perform cleanup operations.  Granular absorbents were used to remove the product from the asphalt road surface and the waste was swept up and collected for disposal.  A small amount of product was believed to have entered a storm drain near the spill site.  The drains down gradient of the spill site were inspected, and no product was found.  Absorbent boom was left in the drains as a precaution and removed on August 21, 2009.
In transit pen hole leak developed in drum. Transporter took immediate action to clean up spill and notify all appropriate agencies.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop for the purpose of conducting a load check.  During this inspection, it was identified that a container within the trailer was punctured by a pallet that shifted in transit allowing approximately 4 gallons of material to escape onto the floor of the van trailer.  The driver secured the vehicle and reported the event to his hoe dispatcher.  A response crew was dispatched to the driver's location.  Upon arrival, the crew donned appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer and proceeded to absorbed all free liquids and decontaminate the trailer floor. The damaged container along with all clean-up debris was placed into a suitable container and prepared for continued transportation.  Once secured, the driver was allowed to continue his trip.
column169: The crew responsible for loading the trailer was re-instructed on the load load securement requriements that must be taken before releasing a vehicle into transportation.  In addition, they have been infomrmed that further instances will not be tolerated and they will be subject to disciplinary action up to and including termination.

column168: Driver returned back from his line run and upon doing his post-trip inspection found that his lead trailer had a liquid leaking out of it.  Immediately went to get help once it was determined this was a haz/mat spill.  The area was secured, so no one would become exposed.  At that time, the safety department was notified and further instructions were given on how to contain the spill.  At that time the trailer door was opened and it was discovered that one five-gallon can of adhesives had been damaged and approximately one-half gallon had been lost.

column168: Drum was transported from origin facility to FAC.  While in transit, drum was damaged due to improper preparation of material.  Cardboard was not placed between the drum and the metal surface it sat on.  During the transfer, the drum's seal malfunctioned because of the constant force being presented to the drum.  Hazmat was immediately placed into a salvage drum and sealed. Material fumes, however, were exposed to all freight in trailer throughout the duration of the transit.
column169: Keep all Hazmat close to the rear of trailer for easy access.  If a drum is present, make sure to use the right kind and amount of dunnage to secure the shipment.  Never set a drum on metal for transport.  Drum should have been tied to the wall as well for safe movement.

column168: During transit the four drums loaded on the pallet shifted causing one of the drums to rupture on a raised nail-head on the pallet. column169: Having cardboard between the drum and the pallet top may have limited the chance of rupture.  Securing of freight to prevent side shifting during transit would have also lessened the potential for damage.

column169: EPCO Carbon Dioxide Products Inc. is having the rail car GATX 300517 transported to the Manufacturer to perform an inspection to determine the route cause of the liquid valve failure and have the necessary repairs made. column168: August 4, 2009: During a routine inspection, FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector R.A. Dedow noted the vacuum relief valve on tank car UTLX 204121, containing the residue of Petroleum Distillates, NOS (3, UN 1268, PGIII, shipped from Kinder Morgan, Carteret, NJ, for return to Citgo Petroleum, Lemont, IL) to not be seated properly and passing by vapor.    Shipper/offeror of tank car, Kinder Morgan, Carteret, NJ, contacted via CHEMTREC by CR Risk Manager A. Richter.  Mr. Brian McGeehan, representative of the shipper, advised he had contracted with mobil repair unit of UTC to repair/replace the vaccum relief device.  Mr. Richter advised Mr. McGeehan that if the fitting were replaced or removed for any purpose, the car would require a bubble-leak test prior to movement.    Mr. McGeehan contacted Mr. Richter a few days later, indicating the car's vaccum releif device had been changed out, in kind, and that movement approval was obtained from the FRA to have the car moved onto a shop (UTLX shop, Marion, OH) for further inspection, and bubble leak test prior to being placed back into service.  I'd also requested that UTC have the original defective vaccum relief device forwarded to the UTC representative on the AAR-Tank Car Committee.

A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbors' in-transit storage facility for the purpose of consolidating less than the truck load quantities of containers onto a single vehicle for the purpose of continuing transportation.  During the transfer operation, a pallet containing several non-bulk packages failed when it was being moved with a fork-lift allwoing one container to fall.  The container struck the inside wall of the trailer causing a gash to develop in the side of the container.  As a result of the incident it is estimated that approximately five (5) gallons of material escaped from the package onto the floor of the trailer.  A response team was assembled and utilizing appropriate protective equipment, the team entered the trailer and placed the damaged container into a suitable salvage drum.  All free liquid was absorbed with a suitable absorbent material and placed into the salvage drum along with all materials used to decontaminate the trailer floor.  Once secure, the container was placed on the alternative vehicle for continued transportation.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence the individuals involved in the loading and unloading operation at this location have been retrained to ensure they inspect all containers and pallets before they initiate the movement in order to ensure each container is evenly distributed on the pallet and that the pallet itself is free of any visible defects or damage that could compromise the structural integrity of the pallet.

column168: The carriers operator struck the IBC with the fork blades while loading. The punture was in the lower 1/3 of the IBC. This caused the release. The terminal manager ordered the IBC removed from the dock to protect the employees. Upon removing the trailer from the dock the material spilled into a storm drain located adjacent to the door the trailer was being moved from. Approx 30 gallons was released into the drain. The manager ordered the material to be moved to the far corner of the facility. During the transit of the material to the location marked by the manager the material continued to spill out of the container into the carriers lot. While the employees were covering the material with oil dry as ordered by the manager the IBC earlier placed at the far end of the facility had started to produce small flames and smoke. At this time the fire department responded. U/A of the fire dept. the IC had determined this to be a haz mat incident and the necessary equipment was dispatched to the facility. The material that had earlier spilled on the ground started to react with the oil in the asphalt and produced several hot spots and flare ups around the facility. The determination was made to evacuate the premises. Immediately upon notification to the company's haz mat and environmental manager an emergency response clean up team was dispatched. The fire department cleared the clean up team was allowed access to the scene to begin the work at 15:30. The clean up continued until approx 20:00. The fire department provided and engine to supply water during the clean up. The fire departmnet was advised to flush the drain with copius amounts of water as this was a water treatment material. One employe was hospitalized for 3 days and treated for respritory distress. He had a pre existing condition which intensified the effects of the exposure. The other employee was treated and released. The incident was concluded on August 21 and all material both debris and remaining product were disposed of according to regulations. No further actions are necessary at this time.

column168: A motorcyle was accepted in Cinniatti OHIO by Nippon Express. The shipment was described as not hazardous by the shipper ( ANARCHY MOTORCYLES) . Nippon Express sent the shipment to Nippon Express at CHICAGO, WHO booked and tentered to LUFTHANSA CARGO in CHICAGO. LUFTHANSA CARGO checked and found the motorcycle to be a dangerous goods, i.e. fuel was in the tank and there was a battery, in fact the motorcycle started right up.( it was packed in a wooden crate )
column169: Lufthansa Cargo contacted the local FAA office in Chicago,who inspected the motorcycle was found it also to be a hazardous material.   The shipment was not accepted for transport and was returned to the local NIPPON EXPRESS OFFICE.   Corrective action by NIPPON EXPRESS, the Cincinatti office said they will no longer accept shipments from this shipper. The Chicago office of NIPPON EXPRESS did not give any corrective action yet.   Corrective action by the shipper, ANARCHY MOTORS, is none . They did not give any corrective action or even express regret at the error of having a hidden DGR to NIPPON.  Lufthansa Cargo could not reach them via telephone, the phone # from website is disconnected ( 513-947-0000). The phone number given by NIPPON EXPRESS was the voice mailbox of a person, who did not answer and mailbox was full.

column168: Portable tank was being towed by 3/4 ton pickup truck.  While enroute to destination, material in tank began to slosh, causing tow vehicle to lose control.  when the truck/tank combination left the roadway, the overturning tank caused the truck to overturn also.  The rollover cracked the polyethylene tank shell causing an immediate loss of 950 gallons of product to the soil along the side of the highway.  All product soaked into the soil.  ACT was hired to stabilize the site and assist with the removal of the tank and truck.
column169: New policy has been implemented where these tanks are no longer utilized to transport any material.

column168: Driver stated the operator went to close the storage tank valve.  He thought the valve was closed and removed the hose from the pump.  The storage tank valve had been closed and product back flowed spilling about 15 gallons.

On August 28, 2009 at 18:30 hrs., personnel in the CSXT East Chicago Transflo Yard, discovered TILX110166, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid Solution, venting from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2009-08-28-00159). Transflo dispatched their own employees to the scene and they found the liquid line was not properly secured. A Transflo employee secured the fittings and the vapor release stopped. The car did not release any liquids, just vapors when the car was in process of switching operations.    Cause code: 242  NARRI: 5(5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

column168: The Conductor was walking his inspection of the train when he noticed that tank car GATX 72836 was emitting a small amount of vapor.  The Conductor notified the East Deerfield yard train master and advised him of the problem and told him that it appeared only once and then did not appear again.  The train master notified the local Fire Department to advise them and to let them know that it happen suddenly and that it stopped and there was no need of a response.  The train master notified railroad operation which called the owner of the car and the customer who was going to receive the car.  Holland Chemical, the owner of the product in the car, called Rescar Corp ... to come to the railyard to fix the ruptured disk.  After Rescar repaired the car the railroad delivered it to Holland Chemical to be emptied and further inspected by the FRA and Holland Chemical.
column169: My only comment in the transportation of hazardous chemicals is that we continue to be observant and concerned with the proper and safe handling of all hazardous chemicals.

column168: Driver had successfully completed transferring the product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank with no problems.  When he was unhooking the transfer hose and trying to cap the end of the hose, he had one end of the hose resting against his knee and it slipped down to the ground.  Spilled about 1/2 gallon of residue that hadn't been drained from the hose yet. Absorbent was immediately put on it to prevent it from spreading and then cleaned up.
column169: The driver received performance enhancement training to review safe hose disconnect procedures.

column168: While transferring product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank, a drip was noticed coming from a weld on the elbow between the internal and external valve on the discharge assembly.  A bucket was put under it and the offloading was continued because of the very slow drip.
column169: After the trailer was cleaned, the whole discharge assembly was replaced.

column168: Driver was headed up a steep hill in the consignee's driveway when he noticed product spraying out of the top of the cargo tank.  He stopped and found that the rear washout cap had come off.  He replaced the cap and cleaned up the spill with the assistance of the customer.
column169: The driver had checked the washout caps before he went to the shipper to load but failed to check to make sure they were tight and not cross threaded when he left the shipper.  He received Safety counseling the next day for not following proper procedure.

column168: A Clean Harbor's driver was dispatched to the shipper's locatin for the purpose of loading a shipment of sodium hydroxide form 2 separate on site storage containers.  During the loading process, the shipper requestd that we include in the pick up addiotnal material comprosed of the same waste stream from two additonal storage containers.  The additonalloading operation was completed and the driver secured the cargo tank's closure devices in preparation for transportation.  Once secured, the driver proceeded to the facility's guard shack in ordert o sign out pror to departure.  While at the guard shack, the driver noticed that material was escaping from the top dome cover of the cargo tank.  The driver immedialtey reported the release and secured the area pending the arrival of an emergency reposne crew.  Upon arrival, the crew, wearing appropriate personal protective equipment  approached the vehicle and upon inspection of the tank, it was decided to off-load the material back into the original storage tanks as it was evident that a reaction was occuring that was creating a pressure buildup within the container.  The crew oened the dome hatch to relieve the pressure and initiated a transfer operation to move the material back into the origial storage vessels in order to allow the shipper the opportunity to stabilze the material.  This operation was done without incident.  In addition, the crew decontaminated the cargo tank and containerized approximatley 4 x 55 gallon containers of contaminated soil.  Once the cargo tank was cleaned and secured and the contaminated debris was containerized, the driver secured the vehicle and departed the site.
column169: At the conclusion of the response activities, it was determined that the two additional containers we were asked to include in the shipment were, in fact not identical.  It has been reported that the additional material contained aluminum in addition to the sodium hydroxide and this is what cause the pressure build-up.  The shipper will reevaluate the waste stream and ensure that all components are properly identified and stored in such a way to preclude an adverse condition while in storage or transportation.  In addition, it was observed that when the man way was opened that the gasket appeared to be misaligned.  It is not clear if this was an error of the part of the driver when the man way was secured or it was caused by the over pressurization.  The driver has been re instructed on the proper procedure for securing a man way and a new gasket was installed in this unit.

column168: Southwest Mechanics were dispatched from PHX to SFO to perform maintenance on an aircraft.  After mechanics finished with their change out of a fuel contaminated part, there was some miscommunication between them and the Ramp Supervisor about the proper storage and shipment of the part.  The part was not secured in one of the pre-determined storage areas.  Instead it was left on the baggage cart. The next morning, the mechanics, their tools and the part in question were loaded onto an aircraft to PHX.

08/05/09 1430 - Freight in question arrived TNXE/ORD dock where it was visually inspected, counted and signed for by our terminal manager.  Freight loaded onto destination trailer at 1739.  08/05/09 2345 - TNXE driver arrived at Midamerica Airport dock, opened trailer doors and detected an odor.  No signs of leakage within trailer were found.  Entire contents of trailer (multiple shipments - both haz and non-haz) unloaded onto airport dock.  One of the two shrink-wrapped skids containing MEK was then disassembled.  An external inspection of the boxes by dock personnel did not reveal any to be damaged, wet or leaking.  Dock personnel notified their chain of command.  The shipper and Chemtrec were contacted.  Fire Department arrived.  A hazmat team arrived. TNXE driver and facility personnel were evacuated 150 feet from the building. Evacuees were updated every 15-20 minutes by liaison coordinator as to progress.  Initial search by hazmat team unsuccessful in determining which boxes were causing the odor.  All boxes were then opened.  Three boxes, when the interior plastic bags were opened, caused their readings to spike to 160 ppm.  These three boxes were then segregated and placed in a drum.  These boxes contained nine (9), 1-Liter plastic bottles with a cardboard separator placed in a plastic bag.  The plastic bottles had screw-on caps, none of which were found to be loose.  According to the hazmat team leader, whereas no leakage was observed in the plastic bags, MEK evaporates at an extremely fast rate.  The cause of the vapor release was undetermined.  08/06/09 0515 - TNXE driver advised he was awaiting decision as to how much freight was going to be accepted/rejected.  08/06/09 0645 - TNXE driver advised the entire hazmat shipment consisting of Printing ink-related material and MEK was refused and loaded back onto his trailer minus the three boxes in the drum being held  at the airport facility dock; all other non-haz shipments and one other Class 3 hazmat shipment (Isopropanol) were accepted to forwarding to their respective destinations.
column169: At the post-incident interview with our driver, I learned that while evacuated, he was twice approached and asked details of the hazardous materials he transported to the facility. Both times he directed the questioner to the facility personnel who was last in possession of the shipping papers before the evacuation.  I was in possession of copies of the hazmat shipping doc information for all three Class 3 hazardous shipments as well as the three pertinent ERG page numbers.  If needed, I thought an official at the site would've called the carrier for this information.  Should this ever happen again, I'll know to keep in more frequent communication with our driver and ask better questions.

column169: The preventability of this incident is not clear and thus, shall be ruled non-preventable. There may have been steps taken that could have prevented this incident, but it is felt that everyone in this situation acted reasonably and as trained to. What was learned here, is that pumps can shift/twist in their mounts and that PTO shafts have separated in this fashion, in the past. This is contradictory to what a number of our professionals had assumed was physically possible, in the past. So we ask that all Drivers and Maintenance Personnel be aware of this potential issue, know the equipment and it's limitations well, and inspect it accordingly, at every opportunity. We also recommend an investigation by our maintenance department of a more secure installation of PTO driven pumps to keep them from twisting on their own, fitting PTO shafts with the female end facing forward, and installing a retention mechanism to keep PTO shafts from falling to the pavement or being whipped around, if they become detached at either end, to reduce the risk of further damage/injury.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE BEING ALLOWED TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!  BETTER STACKING AND USE OF DECK BARS.

column58: Liquid Valve; Loading or Unloading Lines
column168: Driver had finished loading propane truck and had disconnected his fill hose. Driver was carrying loading hose back to storage rack when he dropped the hose resulting in hose end valve coming open and releasing propane.     Driver attempted to shut piping valving when the vapor cloud reached a source of ignition and resulted in a flash fire. Propane release and fire lasted approximately 5-10 seconds.     Flash fire activated emergency shut off system which closed down tank and piping shut off valve.     Driver received burns during flash fire and moved about 30 feet along fence line and waited for emergency responders.
column169: Damage to emergency shut off system resulting from the fire has been repaired.     Loading at facility has been suspended until piping system can be re-plumbed and loading point moved to opposite end of facility.      We have conducted a refresher training on September 11, 2009 of proper loading procedures.

column168: DART TRUCKING DRIVER CALLED THIS WRITER AT 15:30PM THE DRIVER WAS AT A T/A IN WATERBURY, CT. HE DID AN INSPECTION OF THE LOAD AND DISCOVERED A POOL OF LIQUID ON THE DRUM LID.  DRIVER CALLED THIS WRITER.  DRIVER INSTRUCTED TO CALL STATE OF CT., DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION.  RICHARD SCALORA.  CLEAN HARBORS FROM BRAINTREE, MA FACILITY RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  NO SPILLAGE HIT THE GROUND.  CONTAINED ON DRUM LID ONLY.  ONE DROP OF SPILLAGE ON WOODEN PALLET.  CLEAN HARBORS CLEANED UP SPILL; BOTH BUNGS ON DRUM WERE LOOSE.  CHEJ. CLEANED UP SPILL, DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO DESTINATION AT 19:15PM.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS TRAINED IN THE OSHA 40 HOUR HAZWOPER AND THE HAZ FAMILIARIZATION AND AWARENESS TRAINING.  THE DRIVER RECOGNIZED THE SPILLAGE IMMEDIATELY, UPON DOING HIS SCHEDULED LOAD CHECK.  THE DRIVER DID AN EXCELLENT JOB IN HANDLING THE SPILL AS A FIRST RESPONDER.  ALL PARTIES WERE CONTACTED STAT.  THE DRIVER DOCUMENTED ALL PHASES OF CLEAN UP.  THE DRIVER WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN ABLE TO DETECT THE LOOSE BUNGS.  THAT IS CLEAN HARBORS RESPONSIBILITY TO ENSURE ALL BUNGS & LIDS ARE TIGHT.

column168: DRIVER HAD FINISHED LOADING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AND HAD UNHOOKED THE HOSES AND PLACED THEM IN THE RACK.  AS HE WAS TURNING AROUND, THE BOTTOM OF HIS REQUIRED SAFETY COAT CAUGHT THE HANDLE ON THE LIQUID LINE.  BEING UNDER 100 LBS OF PSI, THE LINE CAME UNCRADLED AND BEGAN FLOPPING AROUND.  THE DRIVER WAS SPRAYED WITH AMMONIA FROM THE WAIST DOWN WHILE TRYING TO GET TO THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF.  DRIVER WAS ABLE TO HIT EMERGENCY SHUT OFF.
column169: TRAINING OF DRIVERS TO BE MORE ALERT TO SURROUNDINGS WHILE LOADING AND UNLOADING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND POSITION SELF OUT OF DIRECT LINE OF VALVE OPENINGS.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: THE EPCO TRUCK, WHILE ENROUTE FROM MONROE, WI TO CHICAGO, IL ON I-90 EAST BOUND THE DRIVER OBSERVED THE TRAILER VENTING ABNORMALLY.  THE DRIVER PULLED OVER ON THE SHOULDER OF THE OFF-RAMP LEADING TO I-290 EAST TO CHECK WHICH RELIEF VALVE WAS     RELIEVING.  IT WAS THE 3" MAIN RELIEF VALVE.  THE 3" MAIN RELIEF VALVE SHOULD NOT RELIEVE UNTIL THE PRESSURE IN THE TRAILER VESSEL REACHES 350 PSIG.  THE PRESSURE ON THE VESSEL AT THAT TIME WAS ONLY 230 PSIG.  THE VALVE MALFUNCTIONED.  THE DRIVER    ATTEMPTED TO CAUSE THE VALVE TO RE-SEAT BUT WAS UNABLE.  THIS VALVE MALFUNCTIONED AND WOULD NOT RE SEAT.  THE VALVE CONTINUED TO VENT UNTIL ALL THE PRESSURE WAS OFF THE VESSEL.  AT THIS TIME THIS VALVE IS UNDER INVESTIGATION.
TO BE ENTERED IN QC2 PHASE
column169: (Incident Description continued) Instead, it appeared that someone had poured silicone around the manway. The silicone had degraded. The piece we recovered was about 1/2-inch thick. Our operator applied the correct gasket which he "borrowed" from the driver. The driver commented that he carried the gasket because of his experience with similar issues with other isotainers he had hauled.Total Response Cost of $7,500 as stated in Item 32 represents time spent by 5 Kraton people addressing the incident. Corrective Action:* Safely unloaded the tank without further release of material.* Applied a correct gasket and inspected the tank to ensure there were no other issues prior to release.* Communicated to the carrier and tank owner that the incident was unsafe, unacceptable, not in compliance with transportation regulations, and needed to be addressed by them.* Communicated the incident to Kraton Global Procurement requesting them to address the issue with the supplier for resolution and prevention of future issues.* Completed and submitted "Incident Report" to the U.S. DOT for awareness and appropriate action.

column168: DART TRUCKING DRIVER MR. DAVIS SHEDDEN, DISCOVERED THE SPILLAGE FROM HIS TRAILER (NEAR THE NOSE) (FRONT) - WITH LIQUID WASTE SPILLAGE GOING ONTO THE GRAVEL ON HIS PROPERTY NEAR THE TANDEMS OF HIS TRACTOR.  HE IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO DART TRUCKING SAFETY DEPT.  HE THEN CALLED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE ON THE MANIFEST - 1-877-577-2669.  MR. SHEDDEN TRIED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLABE @ 2 VESSELS DIRECTLY UNDER THE TRAILER WHERE IT WAS LEAKING.  THE RESPONSE AND REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT SAME TIME AFTER MIDNIGHT ON 8-24-09.  THE CO. WAS ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES OF VERMONT, NC.  CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED AT APPROX. 12:00 NOON 8-24-09.  THERE WERE 6 DRUMS OF GRAVEL AND CONTAMINATED SOIL.  AND ONE DRUM OF WASTE.  7 TOTAL.  THIS WASTE WAS TRANSPORTED FROM SCENE 9-1-09.  PA DEP ON SCENE - ERIC HOTTENSTEIN.  MR. SHEDDEN HAD NEGLECTED TO CALL THEM IMMEDIATELY, AS THE CONTIGENCY PLAN DETAILS.
column169: MR. SHEDDEN AND ALL OF DART TRUCKING CO., IND. DRIVERS ARE CONTINUALLY TRAINED IN HAZ CARGO SECUREMENT, AND RECOGNITION OF HAZ DRUMS (OR VESSEL) INTEGRITY.  IT WAS IMPOSSIBLE FOR MR. SHEDDEN TO DETECT THE SINGLE DEFECTIVE DRUM WITH 2 PINHOLES ON BOTTOM OF DRUM, NEAR LOWER RING.  THE DEFECTIVE DRUM LEAKED BECAUSE OF CORROSION AND AGE - FROM THE INSIDE OF THE DRUM - 2 PIN HOLES.  MR. SHEDDEN ACTED RESPONSIBLY AND PROFESSIONALLY IN THE HAZ SPILL RECOGNITION, MITIGATION, MEDIATION, AND ULTIMATE VERFICATION OF THE SERIOUS SITUATIONS.  DRUMS (92) WERE LOADED FROM FRONT TO REAR OF TRAILER.

ALL DRUMS MUST BE BLOCKED AND BRACED TO PREVENT MOVEMENT AND FALLING OVER WHILE THE UNIT IS MOVING.  USE LOAD LOCKBARS, STRAPS AND MTY PALLETS TO ENSURE LOAD IS SAFE AND SECURE BEFORE MOVING.  PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND/OR DUNNAGE.  USE DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCKBARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF!  RETRAIN CREWS IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGE STATING, NOTE WHAT PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER TO MAKE SURE LIDS ON DRUMS ARE SECURED.

column168: 1.ON THE MORNING OF AUGUST 31, 2009, ROLL OFF BOX T-1097 WAS SCHEDULED TO BE SHIPPED TO CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT FOR DISPOSAL.  BOX T-1097 CONTAINED BRINK FILTER ELEMENTS WITH SULFATE.  CUSTOM ECOLOGY INC. (CEI) DRIVER, TYREES HOZE, PICKED UP THE BOX LOCATED AT THE RHODIA FACILITY.  AFTER MR. HOZE PICKED UP BOX T-1097, HE AND RHODIA EMPLOYEE, CHADE BASSO WASHED OFF THE ROLL OFF BOX AND INSPECTED IT FOR LEAKS PER NORMAL PROCEDURES.  BOTH MR. HOZE AND MR. BASSO DETERMINED THAT THE BOX WAS NOT LEAKING AND WAS FIT FOR TRANSPORTATION.  MR. BASSO RELEASED MR. HOZE AND BOX T-1097 AT APPROXIMATELY 7:10 A.M. WHILE IN TRANSIT, MR. HOZE WAS PULLED OVER BY STATE POLICE TROOPER RICHARD ELLIOT AT 8:48 A.M. NEAR MILE MARKER 54 ON I-10 WESTBOUND.  TROOPER ELLIOT STOPPED MR. HOZE BECAUSE BOX T-1097 WAS LEAKING WHILE IN TRANSIT.  TROOPER ELLIOTT CONTACTED CHEMTREC WHO CONTACTED ROBERT MUSSELMAN AT RHODIA.  MR. MUSSELMAN CONTACTED UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (USES) TO ASSIST IN MITIGATING THE INCIDENT AND DECONTAMINATION OF ANY AFFECTED AREAS.  IN A COLLABORATED EFFORT, RHODIA, USES AND CEI SOLIDIFIED THE REMAINING FREE LIQUID IN THE ROLL OFF BOX AND PATCHED THE ROLL OFF BOX.  THE CONTAMINATED AREA WAS CLEANED AND RESIDUE FROM THE DOCONTAMINATION WAS PLACED IN THE ROLL OFF BOX FOR DISPOSAL AT CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT.  THE ROLL OFF BOX WAS DELIVERED TO CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 P.M. WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: E11 WAS DISPATCHED TO THE GENERAL AREA AS INDICATED WITH FOR THE REPORT OF A TANKER FIRE.  AT THE INITIAL DISPATCH THE EXTENT AND EXACT LOCATIOIN WERE UNCLEAR DUE TO LIMITED CELL PHONE COVERAGE IN THE AREA.  A SHORT TIME EARLIER LD 4 (FARRELL) LEFT STA. 11 FOR DENVER VIA LOVELAND PASS.  MOMENTS AFTER THE CALL WAS DISPATCHED, LD 4 ARRIVED ON SCENE AND REPORTED A FULLY INVOLVED TANKER TRUCK AT MM223.  LD 3 (GREENE) AND BATTALION 8 (DAVIS) WENT ENROUTE FROM KEYSTONE E11 (BREWER) WENT ENROUTE FROM SUMMIT COVE AND E2 (ISEMINGER) WAS DIRECTED TO PICK UP THE TENDERS FROM STA. 10.  WHILE ENROUTE LD 4 ADVISED THAT HE HAD THE DRIVER WITH HIM WHO AT THE TIME APPEARED UNHARMED.  ALSO ADVISED THAT THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING A LOAD OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID, A MIXTURE OF GAS AND DIESEL, WITH QUANTITIES VARYING.  AT THAT TIME E8 (BELL) WAS REQUESTED TO RESPOND FROM DILLON TO PROVIDE MORE MANPOWER.  E7 (HOEHN) CALLED FROM THE FRISCO AREA AND WAS DIRECTED TO REPORT TO STA. 8 FOR COVERAGE.  BATTALLION 8 ARRIVED ON SCENE AND ASSUMED LOVELAND PASS COMMAND.  LD 4 ADVISED 3800 GALS. OF DIESEL AND 3500 GALS. OF UNLEADED AND CONFIRMED TWO BLEVES SHORTLY AFTER HE ARRIVED ON SCENE.  LD 3 ARRIVED A SHORT TIME LATER AND THE ICP WAS ESTABLISHED AND OBJECTIVES WERE ESTABLISHED.  E11 ARRIVED ON SCENE AND WAS DIRECTED TO APPROACH THE SITE AND GIVE SPECIFICS ON RUNOFF, EXTENT OF FIRE INVOLVEMENTS TO VEGITATION AND ESTABLISH A DROP TANK SETUP FOR THE SHUTTLE OPERATION.  THE OBJECTIVE WAS TO CONTAIN RUNOFF INTO THE WATERSHED AND APPLY FOAM AS NEEDED TO THE BRUSH AT THE BOTTOM OF THE SLOPE WHERE THE RUNOFF WAS BURNING.  E11 WAS DESIGNATED AS SUPPRESSION AND PROCEEDED UP TO THE SITE.  LD 2 AND LD 3 ARRIVED ON SCENE A SHORT TIME LATER AND WERE ASKED TO ASSIST WITH MEDIA, FS, ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH, DENVER WATER, AND ALL OTHER NOTIFICATION AS DEEMED NECESSARY.  EVENTUALLY LD I WOULD RETURN TO THE BASIN AREA TO ASSIST WITH COMMUNICATIONS AND LD 2 WOULD BE REASSIGNED TO A SNOKE SIGHTING NORTH OF SILVERTHORNE.  E8 ARRIVED ON SCENE AND WAS BRIEFED VIA FACE-TO-FACE ON THE OBJECTIVES.  THEY WERE ASSIGNED TO ASSIST WITH SETTING UP THE DROP TANK, ADVANCING HOSELINES AND MITIGATING AND RUNOFF AS DIRECTED BY THE CO ON E11.  THE TENDERS ARRIVED A SHORT TIME LATER.  LD 3 ADVISED OF THEIR TRAFFIC PATTERN AND FILL SITE.  THE DROP TANK WAS SET UP AND ALL CREWS WERE IN PLACE TO MITIGATE ANY EXPOSURES.  CSP HAZ-MAT ARRIVED ON SCENE AND WAS BRIEFED ON THE SITUATION.  AFTER A THOROUGH WALKTHROUGH OF THE SITE, HE CONFIRMED OUR "LET IT BURN" STRATEGY AND REQUESTED AN ENGINE AND TENDERS REMAIN ON SCENE WHILE THE REMAINING PRODUCT BURNED OFF.  AT THAT TIME E8 WAS RELEASED TO RETURN TO STA. 8 FOR COVERAGE WHICH IN TURN RELEASED E7.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK WAS CHECKED OUT BY SCA 3 AND LATER RELEASED TO A FD CHAPLAIN DESIGNEE AS ARRANGED BY LD 1.  LD PIO (LIPSHER) ARRIVED ON SCENE AND DEALT WITH THE MAJORITY OF THE MEDIA CONTACTS.  THERE WERE 4 SANDBAGS AND 1 TRAFFIC CONE USED FOR THE CONSTRUCTION OF THE UNDERFLOW DAM.
column169: DRIVER WAS TERMINATED.  COMPANY HAS RETRAINED DRIVERS ON MOUNTAIN DRIVING TO REITERATE SAFETY IS COMPANY'S MAIN CONCERN.
