column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: On 10/21/2010 we delivered a load (12.37 tons) of 29.4 Aqua Ammonia Solutions to TVA-Southaven.  On our return trip from Southaven our driver (Doug Lewis) stopped on the side of Hwy 301 south of Stateline Rd. to check his trailer.  At this time he noticed an ammonia smell and saw a small leak come from under his dust cap on his outlet valve on trailer.  At this time he removed his dust cover and product begun to leak out onto the side of road.  At this time he realized he had not completely shut his valve which he did at this point.  The trailer had a hill left in the trailer from the load to TVA-Southaven.  During this time a person passing by reported a trailer leak incident to Walls Fire Dept.  They responded to the scene of the incident and the responder came in contact with our driver, and he called for backup because of the smell of ammonium and that it was a HAZMAT product leak.  When the Walls Fire Dept. HAZMAT crew arrived, they sent our driver and the first responder to Baptist Memorial Hospital to be checked out and decontaminated.  At this time I was notified by Mike Hancock with the fire dept. and told of the situation.  Mike Hancock told me that he had contacted United States Environmental Services (USES) in Southaven and they were on the way to the scene.  I informed Mike that our company has a contract with USES to assist us in the case of emergency.  At this time I left Monroe, LA en route heading to Southaven to the scene.  On the way I called and talked with Kenneth Hays with USES and he let me know that the clean up was under control and stated that it appeared to him that it was a small amount that had leaked on the ground but that the odor was strong.  He also let me know he had talked with Barry McMaster with DEQ and he had recommended that we remove an inch of the dirt from the area of spill and reseed with grass and put hay on it to keep it from washing.  I told him to go ahead and do what was needed and I would see him when I arrived.  Before I could arrive from the drive from Monroe, Kenneth called and let me know that the clean up was complete and that the driver and first responder were released from the hospital with no injuries.
column169: When we got driver, truck and trailer back to yard in Monroe, LA, we started an investigation of the incident.  We looked at the valve to make sure that the valve was in working order and that it was not damaged.  Finding from our investigation was that the incident was cause due to human error on our driver. This driver had been with the company for 4 years and had been trained annually with our other drivers on the procedure of loading and unloading of Aqua Ammonia Solution.  After the findings of the investigation we terminated the employment of the driver (Doug Lewis) for his actions of not following procedures.

column168: On August 25, 2009 at around 0810 passenger Pedro De Pena checked in two bags for American Eagle Flight 5006, which was scheduled to depart at 0935 from the San Juan Luis Munoz Marin International Airport with destination to the Santo Domingo Las Americas Airport.  At approximately 0815 one of the Transportation Security Administration (ISA) agents advised an American Eagle employee that they needed to contact passenger De Pena in order to open his bag as they had detected a suspicious content in his bag.  ISA agent identified a small, broken, glass jar with a silver liquid spilled inside the bag and immediately notified the Airport Fire and Rescue Department.  By 0845 the ticket counter area and terminal hallway were cleared; employees and passengers were evacuated from the terminal.  The ticket counter was closed for approximately six (6) hours, from 0845-1500.  An area of 150'' around the bag was cordoned off and several local, state and federal agencies coordinated the response efforts.  American Eagle contracted a HAZMAT company to perform the removal and disposition of the spilled substance.  Operations were partially restored by 1500 and fully restored by 1800.    PER ADDITIONAL INFORMATION  THE PASSENGER WAS CARRYING ABOUT 20 POUNDS (NINE KILOGRAMS)OF MERCURY AND ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT SPILLED INSIDE SUITCASE, CALDERO SAID.
column169: Airport Emergency Response Systems were reviewed and enhanced with all affected parities involved.  Awareness was raised with operational departments to prevent and/or respond to similar events (undeclared hazardous materials).
